(&peer.address)\n        .with_label(peer.name.as_deref().unwrap_or(&peer.address));\n    match HttpTarget::new(target_config) {\n        Ok(target) => {\n            coordinator.add_http_target(target);\n            // ...\n        }\n        Err(e) => { /* warn and skip */ }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBut note: `add_http_target` requires the coordinator to have an HTTP pool. If only direct peers are configured (no HTTP nodes), you need to create an empty pool first:\n```rust\nif coordinator.http_pool().is_none() && !config.direct_peers.is_empty() {\n    coordinator.set_http_pool(TransportPool::new());\n}\n```\n\nWait — `coordinator` is behind `Arc` at this point. The mutation methods take `&self` so this works. But `set_http_pool` takes `&mut self`. So set up the pool BEFORE wrapping in Arc.\n\n### 4. Update TransportRegistry\n\nThe registry currently uses `TransportRegistry::with_composite(transport.clone())`. Update to use coordinator-based construction. The registry has a `TransportQuery` impl that the coordinator also implements, so you may be able to pass the coordinator directly or adapt.\n\n### 5. Update message receiving\n\nCurrently uses `MessageReceiver::new(http_pool)`. The coordinator has its own `subscribe()` method that does the same thing. Switch to:\n```rust\nlet (events, coordinator_handle) = coordinator.subscribe(our_routing_key);\n```\n\n### 6. Keep send_text_tiered() working\n\nThe client's outbox uses `send_text_tiered()` which calls `coordinator.submit_tiered()`. This should work automatically since `TransportCoordinator` already implements this.\n\n## Key Files to Modify\n\n- `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs` — main transport construction and wiring (this is the big one)\n- Possibly `apps/client/src/config.rs` if config types need updating\n\n## Important Constraints\n\n- Do NOT change any crate code (reme-transport, reme-core, etc.) — only the client app\n- The `Client<T: Transport>` generic should just work with `TransportCoordinator`\n- Keep the embedded node integration working (it's separate from the coordinator)\n- Keep the TUI transport registry display working\n- Run ALL existing tests — this is a refactor, nothing should break\n\n## Branch Setup\n\n```bash\ngit switch feat/lan-discovery\ngit switch -c feat/client-coordinator-migration\n```\n\n## After Implementation\n\n1. Run `cargo test --workspace` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` and `cargo fmt --all -- --check`\n2. Invoke the `simplify` skill to review and clean up your changes\n3. Commit with a clear message\n4. Push and create a PR with `gh pr create --base feat/lan-discovery`\n5. **Wait for CI**: run `gh pr checks <PR_NUMBER>` every 30s, max 15 attempts. If CI hasn't completed, wait longer.\n6. **Wait for bot reviews**: run `gh api repos/leon0399/reme/pulls/<PR_NUMBER>/comments --jq 'length'` to check for review comments. Wait until at least Copilot has reviewed (usually 2-5 minutes after push).\n7. If CI fails or reviewers find issues, fix, push, and re-check\n8. Only report DONE when CI is green AND you've read and addressed any bot review comments\n9. Report completion to team lead with PR URL",
