            "content": "# Submit API Bundle Format — Design Spec\n\n**Issue:** #159 — Migrate submit API to bundle format (multi-envelope)\n\n**Goal:** Change `POST /api/v1/submit` from accepting a single base64-encoded WirePayload to accepting a binary bundle of length-prefixed frames. Single-message callers send count=1 with one frame. No Transport trait changes — batching is API-level only.\n\n## Design Decisions\n\n- **Transport trait unchanged.** `submit_message(envelope)` stays as-is. Batching is handled at the HTTP API layer only. Minimal blast radius.\n- **Content-Type:** `application/vnd.reme.bundle` — custom vendor type for the binary frame format.\n- **No backward compatibility.** Pre-v1.0, no deployed clients. All callers updated simultaneously.\n- **Best-effort processing.** A batch may partially succeed. Response reports per-frame results.\n\n## Wire Format\n\n### Request\n\n```\nPOST /api/v1/submit\nContent-Type: application/vnd.reme.bundle\n\nBody:\n[count: u32 LE]           // number of frames\n[frame_len: u32 LE]       // byte length of first frame\n[frame: WirePayload bytes] // type discriminator + postcard payload\n...repeated count times...\n```\n\nSame length-prefixed frame format as the `.reme` bundle body, without the file-level header (no magic, no version, no checksum). Frames are raw `WirePayload` bytes (`[type: u8][postcard payload]`).\n\n### Response\n\nOne unified shape for all requests (single or batch):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"status\": \"ok\",\n      \"ack_secret\": \"<base64>\",\n      \"signature\": \"<base64>\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"status\": \"error\",\n      \"error\": \"mailbox full\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nEach entry in `results` corresponds to the frame at that index. Per-frame fields:\n- `status`: `\"ok\"` or `\"error\"`\n- `ack_secret` / `signature`: present on success for messages (absent for tombstones and errors)\n- `error`: present on failure, human-readable reason\n\nA count=1 request returns `results` with one entry. The client reads `results[0]` for its receipt data. Clean, uniform, no special-casing.\n\n## Components\n\n### 1. Bundle body encoding/parsing helpers\n\nA pair of functions for encoding and parsing the bundle body wire format. Used by both the node API (parsing) and transport clients (encoding). Location TBD — either a shared module or directly in the files that need them.\n\n**Encoder** (used by `HttpTarget`, `HttpTransport`, replication):\n```rust\nfn encode_bundle_body(frames: &[&[u8]]) -> Vec<u8>\n```\nWrites `[count: u32 LE]` then `[frame_len: u32 LE][frame bytes]` for each frame.\n\n**Parser** (used by node and embedded node handlers):\n```rust\nfn parse_bundle_body(bytes: &[u8], max_frames: u32) -> Result<Vec<Vec<u8>>, ...>\n```\nReads count + length-prefixed frames. Rejects: empty body, count=0, count > max, truncated frames.\n\n### 2. Node `submit_payload` handler rewrite (`apps/node/src/api.rs`)\n\nCurrent flow: base64 decode -> WirePayload::decode -> dispatch single payload.\n\nNew flow:\n1. Read raw bytes from body (no base64)\n2. `parse_bundle_body` -> Vec of frame bytes\n3. For each frame: `WirePayload::decode` -> dispatch through existing per-message/tombstone logic\n4. Collect per-frame results into `results` array (never `?`-propagate mid-loop — each frame is independent)\n5. Return unified `SubmitResponse { results: Vec<FrameResult> }`\n\nEach frame is processed through the existing `handle_message` / tombstone path unchanged. Preserve the existing per-frame ordering: rate-limit check -> duplicate check -> receipt generation -> enqueue. Do not speculatively generate receipts for frames that will be rejected.\n\n### 3. Rate limiting\n\n**Per-IP rate limiting must move inline.** The current `GovernorLayer` middleware fires once per HTTP request, consuming one token regardless of frame count. With batching, a 100-frame request would consume only 1 token — a 100x amplification.\n\nFix: remove `submit_ip` from the `GovernorLayer` middleware. Instead, check the per-IP rate limit inside the handler after parsing the bundle, consuming N tokens for N frames. Governor's `RateLimiter` supports `check_n` for atomic multi-token consumption.\n\nThe per-routing-key limit (`submit_key`) already runs inline in `handle_message` — no change needed. A frame hitting the key limit produces a per-frame error; remaining frames for other routing keys continue processing.\n\n### 4. `HttpTarget::submit_payload` update (`crates/reme-transport/src/http_target.rs`)\n\nChange both the outgoing request encoding and the response parsing:\n\nRequest:\n- Current: base64-encode WirePayload bytes, send as `text/plain`\n- New: encode as bundle body (count=1, one length-prefixed frame), send as `application/vnd.reme.bundle`\n\nResponse:\n- Current: parse `SubmitResponse { status, ack_secret?, signature? }`\n- New: parse `SubmitResponse { results: Vec<FrameResult> }`, extract first result via `.into_iter().next().ok_or(...)` (never index-access — guard against empty results)\n\n**Both `submit_message` and `submit_ack_tombstone` go through `submit_payload`.** The format change covers both uniformly.\n\n### 5. Legacy `HttpTransport` update (`crates/reme-transport/src/http.rs`)\n\n`HttpTransport` has a separate, independent encoding site that also base64-encodes and POSTs to `/api/v1/submit`. Must be updated to use the same bundle body encoding as `HttpTarget`.\n\n### 6. `MailboxStore::enqueue_batch` (`crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs`)\n\nAdd a batch insert method that wraps multiple inserts in a single SQLite transaction:\n\n```rust\nfn enqueue_batch(&self, messages: &[(RoutingKey, OuterEnvelope)]) -> Result<Vec<Result<(), NodeError>>, NodeError>;\n```\n\nThe outer `Result` is for transaction-level failures. The inner `Vec<Result>` reports per-message results (some may fail with `MailboxFull` while others succeed).\n\nThe existing `enqueue` stays unchanged for single-message callers.\n\n### 7. Body size limits\n\n- **Main node:** increase from 256 KiB to 2 MiB (default). Configurable via node config.\n- **Embedded node:** increase from 256 KiB to 512 KiB. 10 frames of typical messages fit comfortably.\n\n### 8. Embedded node HTTP server (`apps/client/src/tui/http_server.rs`)\n\nSame wire format change:\n- Accept `application/vnd.reme.bundle` content type\n- Parse bundle body\n- Allow batches up to 10 frames (hardcoded limit — the embedded node is a P2P endpoint, not a mailbox server)\n- Process each frame through existing embedded node logic\n- **Per-frame error handling:** a tombstone frame in a batch produces a per-frame error (`\"error\": \"tombstones not accepted\"`), NOT a request-level 400. Valid message frames in the same batch are still processed.\n- Same response format as the main node\n\n### 9. Replication (`apps/node/src/replication.rs`)\n\n`replicate_payload` signature changes from `(payload_b64: String)` to `(payload: Vec<u8>)` (raw WirePayload bytes, pre-decoded from the bundle frame).\n\nReplication re-encodes each payload as a count=1 bundle body using the encoder helper. The replicating node signs this new body with its own identity (no change in signing logic — each node already signs with its own key, not forwarding the original signature).\n\nFor batches, the submit handler calls `replicate_payload` once per frame. This is a clean separation: the submit handler unpacks the bundle, and replication only ever deals with individual payloads.\n\n### 10. MQTT bridge\n\nNo changes. MQTT bridge publishes per-message (not HTTP wire format). It receives decoded `WirePayload` and publishes to MQTT topics. The batch loop in the submit handler calls the MQTT bridge per-frame.\n\n## Configuration\n\nNew node config fields (in `[server]` section):\n- `max_body_size`: body size limit in bytes (default: 2097152 = 2 MiB)\n- `max_batch_size`: max frames per request (default: 100)\n\n## Test Impact\n\n**39 tests across 5 files will need updating:**\n\n| File | Tests | Mechanism |\n|------|-------|-----------|\n| `apps/node/tests/receipt_on_submit.rs` | 5 | Direct HTTP POST, base64 body + old response struct |\n| `crates/reme-core/tests/integration.rs` | 19 | Via `HttpTarget::submit_message` (encoding change) |\n| `apps/node/tests/signed_replication.rs` | 3 | Via `HttpTarget` + signed body bytes change |\n| `apps/client/src/tui/http_server.rs` | 7 | Direct HTTP oneshot + embedded handler |\n| `crates/reme-transport/tests/http_auth_test.rs` | 5 | Wiremock (response deserialization change) |\n\nUnaffected: `EmbeddedTarget` tests (5 tests — bypasses HTTP entirely).\n\n### New tests to add\n\n- Unit test: `parse_bundle_body` with valid/invalid/truncated/oversized inputs\n- Unit test: `encode_bundle_body` round-trip with parser\n- Integration test: submit batch of 10 messages, verify all stored and fetchable\n- Integration test: submit batch with mix of valid/duplicate messages, verify partial success\n- Integration test: submit to embedded node with count=1 and small batch\n- Integration test: per-frame rate limiting (N tokens consumed for N frames)\n\n## Out of Scope\n\n- Transport trait changes (kept as single-message)\n- Batch replication optimization (replicate individually for now)\n- MQTT wire format changes (MQTT uses its own topic-based format)\n- Client-side batch sending (callers always send count=1 via Transport)\n",
