            "content": "# Comprehensive Code Review: `feat/lan-discovery` Branch\n\n**Branch:** `feat/lan-discovery` (15 non-merge commits, +2199/-240 lines across 22 files)\n**Spec references:** WHITEPAPER.md (v0.3), ROADMAP.md (v0.4), Implementation Plan (2026-03-16)\n**Review date:** 2026-03-17\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe branch implements Chunks 1-4 and part of Chunk 7 from the mDNS LAN discovery plan. Core discovery infrastructure (crate, backends, TXT helpers, capabilities, coordinator mutations, controller, runtime integration) is solid and well-structured. All tests pass, clippy and fmt are clean.\n\nHowever, several plan-specified items — including one Critical security mitigation (channel binding) and two Major ones (identity endpoint auth exemption, constant-time verification) — are absent. The client migration to `TransportCoordinator` is incomplete (registry still mutable, `MessageReceiver` not deprecated, `send_text_tiered()` not wired). These gaps should be tracked as follow-up work or addressed before merging.\n\n**Verdict:** Good foundation. Merge-ready with documented follow-up issues, OR address the security items first.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Security Review\n\n### 1.1 CRITICAL: Channel binding not implemented (Chunk 5 / SEC-3)\n\n**Plan:** Dedicated Chunk 5 — mix responder IP:port into `build_identity_sign_data()` so a MITM forwarding a challenge gets a signature that fails verification on a different IP.\n\n**Actual:** `build_identity_sign_data(&challenge, &candidate.to_bytes())` in `controller.rs` — no IP:port. Entire Chunk 5 is absent.\n\n**Impact:** A MITM on the LAN who advertises Bob's routing key can forward Alice's challenge to the real Bob, relay the signed response, and get registered as Bob's direct target. Messages are E2E encrypted so content isn't leaked, but the MITM can blackhole messages (return HTTP 200 without valid receipt).\n\n**Mitigation status:** The threat model doc (`docs/threat-model.md` section 2) explicitly documents this gap and argues that channel binding was *rejected* because receipt-gated direct tier is the correct fix. This is a conscious design decision, not an oversight.\n\n**Recommendation:** Accept the deviation from the plan, but ensure issue #90 (receipt-gated direct tier) is tracked as the actual fix. The plan's Chunk 5 can be formally closed as \"rejected per threat model analysis.\"\n\n### 1.2 MAJOR: Identity endpoint behind Basic Auth on node (SEC-7)\n\n**Plan:** Exempt `/api/v1/identity` from Basic Auth middleware so LAN peers can verify identity without credentials.\n\n**Actual:** Not verified in this diff (node code wasn't changed on this branch). However, the plan agent found the endpoint is inside the auth middleware layer.\n\n**Impact:** If a node has Basic Auth configured, discovery identity probes from LAN peers will fail with 401, silently breaking the discovery flow.\n\n**Recommendation:** Verify and fix in `apps/node/src/api.rs`. This is a one-line router nesting change.\n\n### 1.3 MAJOR: Constant-time candidate iteration broken (SEC-2)\n\n**Plan:** Iterate ALL N candidates with constant-time comparison, no short-circuit on first match.\n\n**Actual:** `controller.rs:verify_peer_identity()` returns `Ok(Some(*candidate))` on first match, leaking timing information about which candidate in the list matched.\n\n**Impact:** Low in practice (attacker must observe sub-millisecond timing differences in HTTP request duration), but the plan explicitly flagged this as a Major finding.\n\n**Recommendation:** Iterate all candidates, store the match, return after the loop.\n\n### 1.4 MEDIUM: Response size guard is bypassable (controller.rs:340)\n\n`resp.content_length().unwrap_or(0) > MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES` — relies on Content-Length header. A malicious peer can omit the header and send an arbitrarily large body. The `unwrap_or(0)` means \"unknown length\" passes the guard.\n\n**Recommendation:** Read with a byte cap: `resp.bytes().await` and check `.len()` post-read, or use a streaming reader with `take()`.\n\n### 1.5 INFO: Routing key privacy (SEC-1) — documented and accepted\n\nBroadcasting `rk` in mDNS TXT records enables passive LAN presence detection. This is documented in the threat model (section 5) and accepted for v0.4.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Architecture Review\n\n### 2.1 Crate isolation: PASS\n\n`reme-discovery` has zero dependencies on `reme-transport`, `reme-identity`, or `reme-message`. The `RoutingKey` type alias (`[u8; 16]`) keeps the crate self-contained. Clean boundary.\n\n### 2.2 Discovery controller placement: PASS\n\nController lives in `apps/client/src/discovery/`, not in `reme-discovery`. This correctly separates low-level mDNS mechanics from app-layer trust decisions (contact matching, identity verification, coordinator mutations).\n\n### 2.3 TargetCapabilities: struct vs bitflags — DEVIATION (acceptable)\n\nPlan specified `bitflags::bitflags!` macro. Implementation uses a plain struct with four `bool` fields. The comment justifies this: \"local configuration, not wire data.\" Functionally equivalent, arguably more readable. No concern unless capabilities grow significantly.\n\n### 2.4 Dual-authority problem: NOT RESOLVED\n\n**Plan:** Convert `TransportRegistry` to read-only view, coordinator becomes single write authority.\n\n**Actual:** `TransportRegistry` still has `add_http_target()` mutation method. `with_composite()` constructor retained. Both registry and coordinator can modify pool state.\n\n**Impact:** Low for now (the discovery controller only writes through the coordinator), but the architectural inconsistency violates the plan's ARCH-6 resolution.\n\n### 2.5 `MessageReceiver` not deprecated\n\nStill exported, used in integration tests. Plan required deprecation — the coordinator's `subscribe()` is meant to replace it.\n\n### 2.6 `fake` module unconditionally public\n\n`reme-discovery`'s `fake` module ships in production builds. Should be gated behind `#[cfg(any(test, feature = \"test-utils\"))]`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Functional Review\n\n### 3.1 `PeerUpdated` event: dead variant\n\n`DiscoveryEvent::PeerUpdated` exists in the enum but is never emitted by either backend. The mdns-sd backend maps `ServiceResolved` (including re-resolutions on address change) to `PeerDiscovered`. The controller handles both `PeerDiscovered` and `PeerUpdated` uniformly, so this isn't broken — but the variant is dead code and the controller's update path is untested via the real backend.\n\n### 3.2 Contact snapshot is stale at runtime\n\nThe `contact_index` passed to the discovery controller is loaded once at `App::new()`. Contacts added via the TUI \"Add Contact\" popup are not reflected. A user who adds a contact while a peer is already advertising on the LAN must restart the app.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either pass a `watch::Receiver<Vec<Contact>>` that updates on contact add, or accept this as a known v0.4 limitation and document it.\n\n### 3.3 `send_text_tiered()` not wired into TUI send path\n\n`app.rs` line 1274 calls `self.client.send_text(...)`, not `send_text_tiered()`. The coordinator handles tier routing internally, but the TUI doesn't surface delivery phase info. The migration is incomplete per the plan.\n\n### 3.4 Update short-circuit checks `addresses[0]` not stored URL\n\n`controller.rs` lines 158-166: the no-op optimization compares `SocketAddr::new(peer.addresses[0], peer.port)` against `entry.url`. But `entry.url` was set to whichever address passed identity verification (which may not be `addresses[0]`). This can cause both unnecessary re-verifications and missed updates.\n\n### 3.5 Browse thread never stops\n\n`mdns_sd.rs`: `ensure_browsing()` spawns a `std::thread` that blocks on `browse_receiver.recv()`. The `browsing` flag is never reset in `shutdown()`. Calling `subscribe()` after `shutdown()` silently returns a dead receiver.\n\n### 3.6 Periodic refresh / stale timeout absent\n\nPlan required 60s stale timeout with proactive re-verification and 5-minute periodic refresh. The controller is purely event-driven — no timers. Stale peers are only cleaned up when the mDNS daemon emits `PeerLost` (TTL expiry). The circuit breaker (2 failures for ephemeral) provides some protection.\n\n### 3.7 Dead conditional in `handle_update`\n\n`controller.rs` line 278: `if address_changed || identity_changed` is always true after the early-return guard at line 274. The condition is tautologically true and should be removed for clarity.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Plan Alignment Summary\n\n### Completed\n\n| Plan Item | Status |\n|---|---|\n| Chunk 1: Discovery crate, types, TXT, fake + mdns-sd backends | DONE |\n| Chunk 2: TargetCapabilities, fetch/quorum filtering | DONE |\n| Chunk 2: Coordinator mutation API | DONE |\n| Chunk 2: Client migration to `Client<TransportCoordinator>` | DONE |\n| Chunk 3: Discovery controller with contact matching, verification | DONE |\n| Chunk 3: max_peers resource limit | DONE |\n| Chunk 4: mDNS startup with graceful degradation | DONE |\n| Chunk 4: Advertise after bind (EDGE-3) | DONE |\n| Chunk 7: `allow_direct_lan` config flag | DONE |\n| Threat model documentation | DONE (bonus) |\n\n### Not done / deferred\n\n| Plan Item | Status | Severity |\n|---|---|---|\n| Chunk 5: Channel binding (SEC-3) | REJECTED per threat model | Critical (plan) / Accepted (decision) |\n| Chunk 4: `/api/v1/identity` auth exemption (SEC-7) | NOT DONE | Major |\n| Chunk 3: Constant-time verification (SEC-2) | NOT DONE | Major |\n| Chunk 2: `TransportRegistry` read-only conversion | NOT DONE | Medium |\n| Chunk 2: `MessageReceiver` deprecation | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Chunk 2: `send_text_tiered()` TUI migration | NOT DONE | Medium |\n| Chunk 2: `trust_mode` / legacy `direct_peers` deprecation | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Chunk 3: `verified_peer_index` by PublicID (EDGE-1/4) | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Chunk 3: `Suspended` state before removal | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Chunk 3: Periodic refresh / `stale_timeout` | NOT DONE | Medium |\n| Chunk 4: TUI discovered-peer indicators | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Chunk 7: `allow_auto_relay`, stranger events, #75 refs | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Config: `bind_interfaces` | NOT DONE | Low |\n| Config: `lan_relay` section | NOT DONE (v0.6 scope) | N/A |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Test Coverage Assessment\n\n### What's tested\n\n- TXT encode/decode: 9 unit tests including edge cases (zero values, overflow, bad hex, missing fields)\n- Fake backend: 5 tests (inject/receive, state machine, multi-subscriber, shutdown)\n- Pool: `replace_target`, `targets_where`, capability-filtered fetch (multiple tests)\n- Coordinator: mutation API tests, capability-filtered quorum tests\n- Controller: 6 unit tests (IPv4/IPv6 URL formatting, stranger filtering, contact index, handle_lost)\n\n### What's NOT tested\n\n- `MdnsSdBackend` — zero tests (requires real multicast; acceptable for CI but should have at least a construction test)\n- `verify_peer_identity()` — no tests (would require reqwest mocking or a local HTTP server)\n- Full async `spawn` event loop — no integration tests\n- `PeerUpdated` code path — untestable (never emitted by any backend, no `inject_updated` on fake)\n- TUI app.rs discovery wiring — no test coverage (acceptable; TUI tests are rare)\n\n### All checks pass\n\n- `cargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets` — PASS\n- `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` — PASS (clean)\n- `cargo fmt --all -- --check` — PASS (clean)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Spec Alignment\n\n### WHITEPAPER.md\n\nThe implementation aligns with whitepaper section 11.6 (Node Identity Verification) for the challenge-response protocol. The decision to reject channel binding deviates from the plan but is architecturally sound per the threat model analysis. The `TargetCapabilities` model correctly implements the trust classification described in section 11.5 (Peer Relay Architecture) — ephemeral targets get SEND-only, stable targets get full capabilities.\n\n### ROADMAP.md\n\nv0.4 deliverables status:\n- [x] `mdns` crate integration (using `mdns-sd`)\n- [x] Service advertisement on client startup\n- [x] Background discovery task\n- [x] Automatic transport registration\n- [ ] UI indication of discovered peers\n- [x] Identity endpoint (pre-existing)\n- [ ] Challenge-response with channel binding (rejected per threat model)\n- [ ] Background identity refresh task\n- [ ] Refresh triggers (periodic, failure, network change)\n- [ ] Configuration options for refresh interval\n\n---\n\n## 7. Recommended Actions\n\n### Before merge (if blocking)\n\n1. **Fix identity endpoint auth exemption** (SEC-7) — nest `/api/v1/identity` outside the Basic Auth layer in `apps/node/src/api.rs`\n2. **Fix constant-time iteration** (SEC-2) — iterate all candidates in `verify_peer_identity`, store match, return after loop\n3. **Fix response size guard** — replace `content_length()` check with post-read byte count\n\n### Track as follow-up issues\n\n4. Receipt-gated direct tier (issue #90) — the actual fix for MITM blackholing\n5. `TransportRegistry` read-only migration\n6. `MessageReceiver` deprecation\n7. `send_text_tiered()` TUI integration\n8. Periodic refresh / stale timeout for discovered peers\n9. Contact list live-reload into discovery controller\n10. `PeerUpdated` emission from mdns-sd backend\n11. `fake` module feature-gating\n12. TUI discovered-peer indicators\n\n### E2E verification\n\nThis is a review task — no implementation changes needed. The branch can be verified by:\n1. Starting two client instances on the same LAN with `lan_discovery.enabled = true` and `embedded_node.http_bind` configured\n2. Both clients should discover each other within 5 seconds via mDNS\n3. Direct messages should succeed without manual peer configuration\n4. `cargo test --workspace --all-features` confirms no regressions\n",
