            "plan": "# Comprehensive Code Review: `feat/lan-discovery` Branch (Revised)\n\n**Branch:** `feat/lan-discovery` (15 non-merge commits, +2199/-240 lines across 22 files)\n**Spec references:** WHITEPAPER.md (v0.3), ROADMAP.md (v0.4), Implementation Plan (2026-03-16)\n**Review date:** 2026-03-17\n\n---\n\n## Context\n\nThis is a revised review that incorporates rationale discovered from git history, PR discussions, and GitHub issues. The original review flagged several deviations from the implementation plan; this revision distinguishes between intentional decisions and actual gaps.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Deviation Rationale\n\n### 1.1 Bitflags replaced with bool struct — INTENTIONAL\n\n**Git evidence:** Commit `bbb29f5` originally implemented `TargetCapabilities` using `bitflags::bitflags!` macro (matching the plan). Commit `8ab075a` explicitly replaced it with a plain struct, with message: *\"Plain struct with bool fields (no bitflags dependency needed)\"*.\n\n**Code comment at `target.rs:234-235`:** *\"This is local configuration, not wire data — plain booleans are clearer than bitflags for flags that are checked individually.\"*\n\n**Assessment:** Sound decision. These four flags are never combined with bitwise ops, never serialized to wire, and are only read individually. A bool struct is more readable, avoids the `bitflags` dependency, and clippy is suppressed with an explanation. No action needed.\n\n### 1.2 Channel binding rejected — INTENTIONAL (4 PRs closed)\n\n**Git evidence:** PRs #84, #85, #86, #87 — four attempts at channel binding, all closed. The final PR (#87) was closed on 2026-03-17.\n\n**Threat model (`docs/threat-model.md` section 2):** Explicitly explains that even with channel binding, a MITM who passes verification can still blackhole messages by returning HTTP 200 with invalid receipt. The correct fix is receipt-gated direct tier (issue #90), not channel binding.\n\n**Assessment:** This is a well-analyzed security decision, not an oversight. The plan's Chunk 5 should be formally marked as \"superseded by #90\". No action needed.\n\n### 1.3 Follow-up items tracked as GitHub issues — INTENTIONAL\n\n| Item | Issue | Status |\n|------|-------|--------|\n| `TransportRegistry` read-only migration | #94 | Open |\n| `MessageReceiver` removal | #93 | Open |\n| Receipt-gated direct tier | #90 | Open |\n| Discovery peer capability policy | #75 | Open |\n\n**Assessment:** Core architectural cleanups were explicitly deferred and tracked. The branch ships working discovery without completing every migration step. Reasonable for iterative development.\n\n### 1.4 Identity endpoint Basic Auth exemption — from closed PR #87\n\n**Evidence:** PR #87 included the auth exemption fix alongside channel binding. When channel binding was rejected, the auth exemption went with it. The fix existed but was discarded with the closed PR.\n\n**Assessment:** This is the one item that should have been extracted from the rejected PR. If any node runs with `basic_auth` configured, LAN discovery identity probes will fail silently (401). **This needs a standalone fix.**\n\n### 1.5 Other deferred items — SCOPE DECISIONS\n\nItems like `send_text_tiered()` TUI wiring, periodic refresh, `verified_peer_index`, `trust_mode`, TUI indicators, and `bind_interfaces` appear to be scope decisions for a v0.4 first pass. The client already routes through `TransportCoordinator` which handles tier selection internally — `send_text_tiered()` is an optimization for surfacing phase info to the UI, not a correctness issue. Periodic refresh is compensated by the circuit breaker (2 failures for ephemeral) and mDNS TTL-based `PeerLost` events.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Rust Async Patterns Review\n\nAnalyzing against the loaded `rust-async-patterns` skill guidelines.\n\n### 2.1 CancellationToken usage — GOOD\n\n`controller.rs:53-89`: The discovery controller uses `CancellationToken` with `tokio::select!` — matches the recommended Pattern 4 (Graceful Shutdown) exactly. Clean shutdown deregisters all tracked peers before returning.\n\n### 2.2 Broadcast channel for events — GOOD\n\n`DiscoveryBackend::subscribe()` returns `broadcast::Receiver<DiscoveryEvent>`. The controller handles `RecvError::Lagged(n)` with a warning (line 72-74) and `RecvError::Closed` as a shutdown signal (line 75). This follows best practices for broadcast channels.\n\n### 2.3 `std::thread::spawn` bridge in mdns-sd backend — ACCEPTABLE with caveat\n\n`mdns_sd.rs:94`: Uses `std::thread::spawn` to bridge the `mdns-sd` crate's `std::sync::mpsc::Receiver` to a `tokio::broadcast::Sender`. This is correct — the `rust-async-patterns` skill warns \"Don't block: Never use `std::thread::sleep` in async\", but this thread is intentionally blocking on a non-async API and bridging into the async world.\n\n**Caveat (from skill \"Don'ts: Don't spawn unboundedly\"):** The browse thread is never joined or cleaned up. After `shutdown()`, the `browsing` flag stays `true`. If `subscribe()` is called after `shutdown()`, the flag check passes, no new thread is spawned, but the old thread's `browse_receiver` channel is closed, so it has already exited. The returned `broadcast::Receiver` will never receive events but won't leak resources. **Low severity — document the post-shutdown behavior.**\n\n### 2.4 Mutex usage in MdnsSdBackend — CORRECT per patterns\n\nUses `std::sync::Mutex` (not `tokio::Mutex`) which is correct since locks are never held across `.await` points. The three-phase pattern (check under lock → work without lock → commit under lock) in `start_advertising`/`stop_advertising` prevents holding locks during I/O, matching the skill's \"Don't hold locks across awaits\" rule.\n\n### 2.5 `reqwest::Client` reuse — GOOD\n\n`controller.rs:104-109`: Single `reqwest::Client` with configured timeouts, reused for all identity verifications. Follows connection pool best practices.\n\n### 2.6 Missing `#[instrument]` — MINOR\n\nThe skill recommends \"Instrument with tracing for debugging async code.\" The `spawn` function and `handle_discovered` could benefit from `#[tracing::instrument(skip(events, coordinator, cancel))]` for better debug spans. Low priority.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Memory Safety Review\n\nAnalyzing against the loaded `memory-safety-patterns` skill guidelines.\n\n### 3.1 Ownership model — CLEAN\n\n- `TransportCoordinator` is `Arc`-wrapped and shared between the controller task and the app. Follows `Arc` for shared ownership pattern.\n- `DiscoveryController` is owned by a single `tokio::spawn` task — no shared access, no `Arc` needed. Clean ownership boundary.\n- `PeerEntry` uses owned `String` for `url` and cloned `TargetId` — no dangling references possible.\n\n### 3.2 `RwLock` in `TransportPool` — SOUND\n\n`pool.rs`: `targets: RwLock<Vec<Arc<T>>>` — `RwLock` for read-heavy target list, `Arc<T>` for targets shared with in-flight requests. The `replace_target` method (line in pool.rs) acquires a single write lock for atomic remove+add. No lock ordering issues.\n\n### 3.3 `TargetHealth` lock ordering — DOCUMENTED\n\n`target.rs:342-353`: Comment explicitly warns about lock ordering between `recovery_started` and `state` in `state()` vs `record_failure()`. The `should_reset` variable is computed before dropping the lock, preventing deadlock. Good defensive programming.\n\n### 3.4 No `unsafe` code — CONFIRMED\n\nZero `unsafe` blocks across all new code. All type conversions use safe patterns (`try_into`, `TryFrom`).\n\n### 3.5 `expect()` usage — ONE INSTANCE, justified\n\n`controller.rs:108`: `reqwest::Client::builder().build().expect(\"failed to build reqwest client\")` — this is an initialization-time panic for an infallible operation (no TLS config that could fail). Acceptable.\n\n`controller.rs:269`: `self.peer_index.get(instance_name).expect(\"invariant: is_update implies entry exists\")` — panic on violated invariant. The caller checks `is_update = self.peer_index.contains_key(...)` before calling. Sound.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Remaining Actionable Findings\n\nAfter filtering out intentional decisions and tracked issues, these are the items that genuinely need attention:\n\n### 4.1 HIGH: Identity endpoint behind Basic Auth (not tracked anywhere)\n\n`/api/v1/identity` is not exempted from auth middleware on the node. This was part of the closed PR #87 and fell through the cracks. Discovery will silently fail on auth-enabled nodes.\n\n**Fix:** One-line router nesting change in `apps/node/src/api.rs`.\n\n### 4.2 MEDIUM: Response size guard is bypassable (`controller.rs:340`)\n\n```rust\nif resp.content_length().unwrap_or(0) > MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES {\n```\n\nA malicious peer omitting `Content-Length` passes this guard with `unwrap_or(0)`. The `resp.json().await` that follows will read the full body into memory.\n\n**Fix:** Use `resp.bytes().await` with a post-read length check, or set a body size limit on the reqwest client builder.\n\n### 4.3 LOW: Dead conditional in `handle_update` (`controller.rs:278`)\n\n```rust\nif !address_changed && !identity_changed { return; } // line 274\nif address_changed || identity_changed { ... }        // line 278 — always true\n```\n\nThe second condition is tautologically true. Remove for clarity.\n\n### 4.4 LOW: `PeerUpdated` never emitted\n\n`DiscoveryEvent::PeerUpdated` exists but the mdns-sd backend maps all `ServiceResolved` events to `PeerDiscovered`. The controller handles both uniformly (line 63-66), so behavior is correct, but the variant is dead code. Consider either emitting it on re-resolution or removing it.\n\n### 4.5 LOW: `fake` module unconditionally public\n\n`reme-discovery/src/lib.rs` exports `pub mod fake` without feature gating. Test infrastructure ships in production. Should be `#[cfg(any(test, feature = \"test-utils\"))]`.\n\n### 4.6 INFO: Update short-circuit uses `addresses[0]` not stored URL\n\n`controller.rs:158`: The no-op optimization for updates compares `SocketAddr::new(peer.addresses[0], peer.port)` against `entry.url`, but `entry.url` was set to whichever address passed verification (which may not be `addresses[0]`). Can cause unnecessary re-verifications or missed updates.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Test & CI Status\n\n- `cargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets` — **PASS** (all tests green)\n- `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` — **PASS** (clean)\n- `cargo fmt --all -- --check` — **PASS** (clean)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Summary\n\n| Category | Count | Notes |\n|----------|-------|-------|\n| Intentional deviations (rationale found) | 5 | Bitflags, channel binding, follow-up issues, scope decisions |\n| Tracked in GitHub issues | 4 | #90, #93, #94, #75 |\n| Actionable findings (this review) | 6 | 1 high, 1 medium, 4 low/info |\n| Async pattern issues | 0 | Clean use of CancellationToken, broadcast, locks |\n| Memory safety issues | 0 | No unsafe, clean ownership, documented lock ordering |\n\n**Verdict:** The branch is well-implemented with intentional, documented deviations from the plan. The one item that fell through the cracks (auth exemption for identity endpoint) should be fixed before or shortly after merge. The response size guard is a defense-in-depth improvement. Everything else is low priority cleanup.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Implementation Plan: Single PR, 5 Commits\n\nOne PR against `feat/lan-discovery` with each fix as its own commit. Run full checks after each commit.\n\n**Verification after each commit:**\n```bash\ncargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets\ncargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings\ncargo fmt --all -- --check\n```\n\n---\n\n### Commit 1: `fix: exempt identity endpoint from Basic Auth`\n\n**File:** `apps/node/src/api.rs`\n\n**Problem:** Lines 87-98 — the `/api/v1/identity` route is merged into the router *before* the `check_basic_auth` middleware layer is applied at line 94. But Axum layers wrap everything above them, so the identity endpoint IS behind auth. LAN discovery peers without credentials will get 401.\n\n**Fix:** Split the router into public and authenticated sections:\n\n```rust\n// Public routes (no auth required)\nlet public_routes = Router::new()\n    .route(\"/api/v1/identity\", get(get_identity))\n    .route(\"/api/v1/health\", get(health_check));\n\n// Authenticated routes\nlet auth_routes = Router::new()\n    .merge(submit_route)\n    .merge(fetch_route)\n    .route(\"/api/v1/stats\", get(get_stats))\n    .layer(DefaultBodyLimit::max(MAX_BODY_SIZE))\n    .layer(middleware::from_fn_with_state(state.clone(), check_basic_auth));\n\n// Combine\nRouter::new()\n    .merge(public_routes)\n    .merge(auth_routes)\n    .with_state(state)\n```\n\nNote: `health_check` should also be public (monitoring probes shouldn't need auth). `DefaultBodyLimit` stays on auth_routes since identity/health have no body.\n\n**Test:** Existing identity endpoint tests in `apps/node/tests/identity_endpoint.rs` should still pass. Add a test that verifies identity endpoint works when auth is configured.\n\n---\n\n### Commit 2: `fix: cap identity response body size`\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`\n\n**Problem:** Line 340 — `resp.content_length().unwrap_or(0)` returns 0 when `Content-Length` header is absent, bypassing the size guard. A malicious peer can omit the header and send an arbitrarily large body.\n\n**Fix:** Read bytes first, then check size:\n\n```rust\n// Replace lines 339-345:\nlet bytes = resp.bytes().await?;\nif bytes.len() as u64 > MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES {\n    debug!(\"Identity response too large ({} bytes), skipping\", bytes.len());\n    return Ok(None);\n}\n\nlet body: IdentityResponse = serde_json::from_slice(&bytes)\n    .map_err(|e| {\n        debug!(\"Failed to parse identity response: {e}\");\n    })\n    .ok()\n    .map_or_else(|| Ok(None), |b| Ok(Some(b)))?;\n```\n\nActually simpler — just replace the `resp.json()` call:\n\n```rust\nlet bytes = resp.bytes().await?;\nif bytes.len() as u64 > MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES {\n    debug!(\"Identity response too large ({} bytes), skipping\", bytes.len());\n    return Ok(None);\n}\nlet Ok(body) = serde_json::from_slice::<IdentityResponse>(&bytes) else {\n    return Ok(None);\n};\n```\n\nThis requires adding `serde_json` to `apps/client/Cargo.toml` (or it may already be there transitively). Check before adding.\n\n---\n\n### Commit 3: `fix: remove dead conditional in handle_update`\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`\n\n**Problem:** Lines 274-278 — the early return at 274 guarantees that the condition at 278 is always true.\n\n**Fix:** Remove the outer `if` at line 278, dedent the block:\n\n```rust\nfn handle_update(...) {\n    let entry = self.peer_index.get(instance_name)\n        .expect(\"invariant: is_update implies entry exists\");\n    let address_changed = entry.url != url;\n    let identity_changed = entry.verified_identity != verified;\n    let old_target_id = entry.target_id.clone();\n\n    if !address_changed && !identity_changed {\n        return;\n    }\n\n    // Build and replace target (always reaches here)\n    let Some(target) = Self::build_http_target(instance_name, url, verified) else {\n        return;\n    };\n    coordinator.replace_http_target(&old_target_id, target);\n\n    if address_changed {\n        info!(instance = %instance_name, old_url = %entry.url, new_url = %url,\n              \"Updated discovered peer address\");\n    } else {\n        info!(instance = %instance_name, \"Updated discovered peer identity\");\n    }\n\n    self.peer_index.insert(\n        instance_name.to_owned(),\n        PeerEntry {\n            target_id: TargetId::http(url),\n            verified_identity: verified,\n            url: url.to_owned(),\n        },\n    );\n}\n```\n\nAlso fix the update short-circuit at line 158 to compare against stored URL:\n\n```rust\n// Line 158: was comparing addresses[0], should compare stored url\nif is_update {\n    let entry = &self.peer_index[&peer.instance_name];\n    // Check if ANY new address matches the stored URL\n    let any_match = peer.addresses.iter().any(|&addr| {\n        let candidate = format!(\"http://{}\", SocketAddr::new(addr, peer.port));\n        entry.url == candidate\n    });\n    if any_match {\n        debug!(instance = %peer.instance_name,\n               \"Update with matching address, skipping re-verification\");\n        return;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Commit 4: `refactor: feature-gate fake discovery backend`\n\n**Files:** `crates/reme-discovery/src/lib.rs`, `crates/reme-discovery/Cargo.toml`\n\n**Problem:** `pub mod fake` ships in production builds. Only used by crate-internal tests.\n\n**Fix:**\n\nIn `Cargo.toml`, add a `test-utils` feature:\n```toml\n[features]\nmdns-sd = [\"dep:mdns-sd\", \"dep:hostname\"]\ntest-utils = []\n```\n\nIn `lib.rs`:\n```rust\n#[cfg(any(test, feature = \"test-utils\"))]\npub mod fake;\n```\n\nNo downstream crates import `reme_discovery::fake`, so no other changes needed. Verify with `cargo build -p reme-discovery` (without `--all-features`).\n\n---\n\n### Commit 5: `fix: emit PeerUpdated for re-resolved mDNS services`\n\n**Files:** `crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs`, `crates/reme-discovery/src/fake.rs`\n\n**Problem:** `ServiceResolved` is always mapped to `PeerDiscovered`, even on re-resolution. The `PeerUpdated` variant exists but is dead code.\n\n**Fix:** Track known fullnames in the browse thread and emit `PeerUpdated` for re-resolutions:\n\nIn `mdns_sd.rs`, the browse thread (line 94):\n```rust\nstd::thread::spawn(move || {\n    let mut known: std::collections::HashSet<String> = std::collections::HashSet::new();\n    while let Ok(event) = browse_receiver.recv() {\n        let discovery_event = match event {\n            mdns_sd::ServiceEvent::ServiceFound(_stype, fullname) => {\n                debug!(fullname, \"mDNS-SD: service found (awaiting resolution)\");\n                continue;\n            }\n            mdns_sd::ServiceEvent::ServiceResolved(info) => {\n                let peer = Self::resolved_to_peer(&info);\n                if known.insert(info.fullname.clone()) {\n                    debug!(fullname = %info.fullname, \"mDNS-SD: service resolved\");\n                    DiscoveryEvent::PeerDiscovered(peer)\n                } else {\n                    debug!(fullname = %info.fullname, \"mDNS-SD: service re-resolved\");\n                    DiscoveryEvent::PeerUpdated(peer)\n                }\n            }\n            mdns_sd::ServiceEvent::ServiceRemoved(_stype, fullname) => {\n                known.remove(&fullname);\n                debug!(fullname, \"mDNS-SD: service removed\");\n                DiscoveryEvent::PeerLost(fullname)\n            }\n            _ => continue,\n        };\n        let _ = tx.send(discovery_event);\n    }\n});\n```\n\nIn `fake.rs`, add `inject_updated`:\n```rust\npub fn inject_updated(&self, peer: RawDiscoveredPeer) {\n    let _ = self.tx.send(DiscoveryEvent::PeerUpdated(peer));\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Final: Run full verification\n\n```bash\ncargo test --workspace --all-features --all-targets\ncargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings\ncargo fmt --all -- --check\ncargo build -p reme-discovery  # verify fake module is gated in default build\n```\n\nThen create PR against `feat/lan-discovery`.\n",
