ead code or document why it is ignored.\n\nThis is lower risk but deserves a brief comment explaining why `_txt_port` is discarded.\n\n---\n\n**3. `inject_updated` in `FakeDiscoveryBackend` has no test coverage**\nConfidence: 80\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/fake.rs`, line 35–37.\n\nThe new `inject_updated` method (commit 5 adds `PeerUpdated` support) has zero test coverage in `fake.rs`. Every other method on `FakeDiscoveryBackend` has at least one test (`inject_peer`, `inject_lost`, `start_advertising`, `stop_advertising`, `shutdown`). This is inconsistent given the project's testing practices and was the exact scenario added in commit 5 to fix a review finding.\n\nFix: Add a test analogous to `inject_lost_and_receive` that calls `inject_updated` and asserts the received event is `PeerUpdated` with the correct peer.\n\n```rust\n#[tokio::test]\nasync fn inject_updated_and_receive() {\n    let backend = FakeDiscoveryBackend::new();\n    let mut rx = backend.subscribe();\n\n    backend.inject_updated(make_peer(\"alice\"));\n\n    let event = rx.try_recv().unwrap();\n    match event {\n        DiscoveryEvent::PeerUpdated(peer) => assert_eq!(peer.instance_name, \"alice\"),\n        other => panic!(\"expected PeerUpdated, got {other:?}\"),\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Observations (below confidence threshold, noted for awareness)\n\n- In `api.rs` the split between `public_routes` and `auth_routes` is clean and correct. `/api/v1/identity` sitting outside `DefaultBodyLimit::max(MAX_BODY_SIZE)` is fine since it is a GET with query params only — no body to limit.\n- The `MAX_IDENTITY_RESPONSE_BYTES = 4096` cap in `controller.rs` is conservative and correct. A valid response is ~120 bytes; 4096 gives ample headroom without being exploitable.\n- The `known` HashSet in `mdns_sd.rs` (line 95) correctly drives the `PeerDiscovered` vs `PeerUpdated` distinction on first vs. subsequent `ServiceResolved` events for the same fullname. Logic is sound.