          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here's the current situation and design proposal for **graceful shutdown of the standalone node** (#128).\n\n## Current state\n\nThe node's `main()` is a straight-line startup → `axum::serve(...).await` that blocks forever. Background tasks (cleanup, MQTT subscriber) are fire-and-forget `tokio::spawn` with no cancellation. On SIGTERM/SIGINT, the process just dies — no WAL checkpoint, no mDNS goodbye (future), no in-flight request draining.\n\n## Approach: `CancellationToken` + `axum::serve().with_graceful_shutdown()`\n\n**Recommended** — single approach here, this is well-trodden Tokio territory with one obvious pattern:\n\n1. Create a `CancellationToken` before spawning any background tasks\n2. Pass token clones to cleanup task and MQTT subscriber so they exit their loops on cancellation\n3. Wire `tokio::signal::ctrl_c()` (+ SIGTERM on unix) to trigger the token\n4. Use `axum::serve(...).with_graceful_shutdown(token.cancelled_owned())` for HTTP\n5. After the server stops, run finalization: WAL checkpoint, log clean exit\n\nFor TLS mode (`axum_server::bind_rustls`), the `axum-server` crate uses a `Handle` for graceful shutdown instead of the `with_graceful_shutdown` method — we'd create a `Handle`, call `handle.graceful_shutdown(timeout)` when the signal fires.\n\n### Design section by section\n\n**1. Signal handling**\n\n```rust\nasync fn shutdown_signal(cancel: CancellationToken) {\n    let ctrl_c = tokio::signal::ctrl_c();\n    #[cfg(unix)]\n    let mut sigterm = tokio::signal::unix::signal(\n        tokio::signal::unix::SignalKind::terminate()\n    ).expect(\"failed to install SIGTERM handler\");\n\n    tokio::select! {\n        _ = ctrl_c => info!(\"Received SIGINT, shutting down...\"),\n        #[cfg(unix)]\n        _ = sigterm.recv() => info!(\"Received SIGTERM, shutting down...\"),\n        _ = cancel.cancelled() => {},\n    }\n    cancel.cancel();\n}\n```\n\nThis is a standalone function. The token is shared with all background tasks.\n\n